2	/**
3	 * detection-spec.js - the detection-spec migration (P3 Wave-2a, breach proposer layer).
4	 *
5	 * The compiled catalogue ships DUTIES AS PROSE: every record's website_obligations[] is a list of
6	 * { duty, elements[], evidence_type } where elements[] are human sentences, not machine patterns
7	 * (catalogue/README.md: "duties are prose, not regex, until a future detection migration"). This
8	 * module IS that migration. It reads the compiled catalogue at RUNTIME and derives, IN MEMORY, a
9	 * machine-checkable DetectionSpec per obligation. The packs are never touched: no pattern is written
10	 * back, nothing here edits a catalogue file (Constitution Rule 2, catalogue/packs are QA-stamped).
11	 *
12	 * A proposer PROPOSES; it never emits a finding. The DetectionSpec is the grammar a proposer runs to
13	 * turn one obligation into a breach CANDIDATE. propose.js is the only evaluator; the verifier and
14	 * adjudicator downstream turn a candidate into (or reject it from) a finding.
15	 *
16	 * ── The DetectionSpec grammar ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
17	 *   {
18	 *     record_id,        // the catalogue record id (upper-snake) this spec checks
19	 *     duty_idx,         // index into record.website_obligations[] (which duty)
20	 *     evidence_type,    // 'presence' | 'absence' | 'behavioural' | 'register' (the obligation's own)
21	 *     surface,          // 'visible_text' | 'raw_html' | 'footer' | 'register_row' | 'browser_lane'
22	 *     patterns: [ { kind, value, negation_guarded } ],
23	 *     page_class,       // the crawl page-class this on-page duty needs (coverage-contract), or null
24	 *   }
25	 *
26	 * evidence_type is the catalogue polarity, verbatim (catalogue/linters/polarity.js SEMANTIC DOCTRINE):
27	 *   - 'presence'    the duty names REQUIRED content; the site breaches when it is MISSING. propose.js
28	 *                   runs this as an ABSENCE-breach (required pattern absent across a COVERED surface),
29	 *                   artifact = coverage_proof. This is the truncation-sensitive, russell-cooke class
30	 *                   (C-024): it fires only with the coverage interlock proven.
31	 *   - 'absence'     the duty names PROHIBITED content; the site breaches when it IS PRESENT. propose.js
32	 *                   runs this as a PRESENCE-breach (prohibited pattern found in visible prose),
33	 *                   artifact = the verbatim quote. negation_guarded is true so the site's OWN compliant
34	 *                   self-declaration ("we do not treat under-18s") is not read as the prohibited claim
35	 *                   (C-048/C-060, the Botox-U18 polarity trap).
36	 *   - 'register'    proved against a pre-fetched register row (evidence/registers), surface
37	 *                   'register_row', page_class null: the crawl never gates it.
38	 *   - 'behavioural' proved by an observed browser action (evidence/browser), surface 'browser_lane',
39	 *                   page_class null.
40	 *
41	 * ── surface = evidence surface, DECLARED per rule (C-035/C-036) ──────────────────────────────────
42	 * A spec's surface is BOTH where propose.js detects AND where it cuts the evidence quote, so a hit and
43	 * its quote can never disagree (C-035, the raw-html-vs-stripped-text bug). The asymmetry of C-036 is
44	 * encoded here, not left to the matcher: a PROHIBITION ('absence') triggers on VISIBLE prose only
